50|$|Pairs of <b>mirror</b> <b>nuclei</b> {{have the}} same spin and parity. If we {{constrain}} to odd number of nucleons (A=Z+N) then we find <b>mirror</b> <b>nuclei</b> that differ one another by exchanging a proton by a neutron. Interesting to observe is their binding energy which is mainly due to the strong interaction and also due to Coulomb interaction. Since the strong interaction is invariant to protons and neutrons one can expect these <b>mirror</b> <b>nuclei</b> to have very similar binding energies.|$|E
